<Documentation>
  <Docs DocId="T:UIKit.UIDynamicBehavior">
    <summary>The base class for items that describe the physics-like behaviors of UIKit Dynamics, introduced in iOS 7.</summary>
    <remarks>
      <para>A number of <see cref="UIKit.UIDynamicBehavior" />s are associated with a <see cref="UIKit.UIDynamicAnimator" />, which is responsible for the overall context. Any given <see cref="UIKit.UIDynamicBehavior" /> is associated with some amount of <see cref="UIKit.IUIDynamicItem" />s (such as <see cref="UIKit.UIView" />s and <see cref="UIKit.UICollectionViewLayoutAttributes" />); most subclasses of <see cref="UIKit.UIDynamicBehavior" /> expose these in an <c>Items</c> property or application developers can retrieve them with <see cref="UIKit.UIDynamicAnimator.GetDynamicItems(CoreGraphics.CGRect)" />.</para>
      <para>There are a number of predefined subclasses of <see cref="UIKit.UIDynamicBehavior" />:</para>
      <para>
        <list type="table">
          <listheader>
            <term>Subclass</term>
            <description>Behavior</description>
          </listheader>
          <item>
            <term>
              <see cref="UIKit.UIAttachmentBehavior" />
            </term>
            <description>
            Attachment: Specifies a dynamic connection between two <see cref="UIKit.IUIDynamicItem" />s or between a <see cref="UIKit.IUIDynamicItem" /> and a fixed point.
          </description>
          </item>
          <item>
            <term>
              <see cref="UIKit.UICollisionBehavior" />
            </term>
            <description>
            Collision: Detects when the boundaries of a <see cref="UIKit.IUIDynamicItem" /> meet another boundary.
          </description>
          </item>
          <item>
            <term>
              <see cref="UIKit.UIGravityBehavior" />
            </term>
            <description>
            Gravity: Accelerates the <see cref="UIKit.IUIDynamicItem" /> towards the bottom of the screen.
          </description>
          </item>
          <item>
            <term>
              <see cref="UIKit.UIDynamicItemBehavior" />
            </term>
            <description>
            Animation: Specifies an animation configuration to apply to one or more <see cref="UIKit.IUIDynamicItem" />s.
          </description>
          </item>
          <item>
            <term>
              <see cref="UIKit.UIPushBehavior" />
            </term>
            <description>
            Pushing: Applies a continuous or instantaneous force vector to a <see cref="UIKit.IUIDynamicItem" />.
          </description>
          </item>
          <item>
            <term>
              <see cref="UIKit.UISnapBehavior" />
            </term>
            <description>
            Snapping: Specifies a magnetism-like attraction between a <see cref="UIKit.IUIDynamicItem" /> and a fixed point. Includes a rebounding effect.
          </description>
          </item>
        </list>
      </para>
    </remarks>
    <related type="externalDocumentation" href="https://developer.apple.com/library/ios/documentation/UIKit/Reference/UIDynamicBehavior_Class/index.html">Apple documentation for <c>UIDynamicBehavior</c></related>
  </Docs>
